# Architecture

## Monorepo Layout

```
viberanium/                  # Game engine (Viberanium)
└── src/
    ├── engine/              # Core loop, registry, scene, entity primitives
    ├── math/                # vec3, quat, mat4 — no deps, no classes
    ├── input/               # createInput — keyboard, mouse, pointer lock
    ├── collision/           # Pure AABB/OBB math helpers (no GL, no registry)
    ├── components/          # Data-only component types + factories
    ├── systems/             # install*System processors (movement, physics, animation, …)
    ├── navigation/          # A* pathfinding helpers
    ├── assets/gltf/         # GLB/glTF loader, cache, runtime scene, materials builder
    ├── render/              # WebGL2 device, passes, pipeline installer
    └── index.ts             # Public barrel export (package entry only)
sandbox/                     # Game content
└── src/
    ├── startup/             # bootstrap, sceneManager
    ├── levels/              # catalog, assets, useLevelScene
    ├── scenes/              # createPlayableScene — generic load/unload factory
    ├── player/              # createPlayer — entity assembly + asset loading
    ├── robot/               # createRobot — NPC assembly + robot AI system
    └── world/               # ground mesh, static props
```

Games import the engine via `import { ... } from 'viberanium'`. Game code never lives under `viberanium/`.

## Game vs Scene Registry

- **Game registry** (`game.registry`) — persistent entities, render pipeline, global input handlers, scene manager
- **Scene registry** (`scene.registry`) — ephemeral; created per level visit, destroyed on exit
- `game.setActiveScene(scene)` unloads the previous scene synchronously before activating the next

Session-scoped caches (`GltfCache`, `TextureCache`) live in bootstrap and survive level transitions. Scene registries, entities, nav grids, and GPU meshes for level content do not.

## Naming Conventions

| Pattern | Example | Use for |
|---------|---------|---------|
| `createX()` | `createTransform()`, `createGltfCache()` | Data factory — returns a plain object |
| `installXSystem()` | `installMovementSystem()` | System installer — registers actions on registry |
| `useX()` | `useRegistry()`, `useLevelScene()` | Engine/game primitive — creates and owns internal state |
| `buildX()` | `buildGltfMaterials()`, `updateNavGridBlocked()` | Pure transform/builder — no side effects |

## Code Style

- Arrow functions everywhere; `function` keyword only in module-level helpers inside `.ts` files
- No `class` in game logic; `class` is acceptable only in render passes where constructor injection is cleaner
- Factory functions return plain typed objects — never extend or subclass them
- Every public-facing factory/installer exports its return type explicitly
- Guard throws at entry: `if (!canvas) throw new Error('Missing #game canvas')`
- **Never** add barrel `index.ts` files inside engine or game source trees — the single exception is `viberanium/src/index.ts` (package public API)

## Adding New Features

Follow the manaburn-barcrawl pattern — add a feature folder under the game package:
```
sandbox/src/enemies/spider/
  spider.ts           # createSpiderEntity
  components/
    spiderAI.ts
  systems/
    spiderSystem.ts   # installSpiderSystem
```
Register spawn logic in a `LevelDefinition` or custom `spawnNpcs` callback. Install feature systems in `createPlayableScene` (or a scene variant) once per scene instance.

When adding geometry that blocks pathfinding, register a static `collider` and call `markNavGridDirty(scene.registry)`.

## Level loading

See `.cursor/rules/levels.mdc` for the full catalog → preload → ephemeral scene → load/unload pattern.
